    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube works by capturing the dynamic pressure of oncoming air, which is the sum of the static pressure and the velocity pressure, allowing the aircraft to calculate its true airspeed. If the opening gets blocked, the dynamic pressure reading becomes zero, causing the instruments to display incorrect speeds, which can be fatal if the pilot relies on it for speed control. This is a critical safety issue because the aircraft's autopilot and flight computers depend on accurate airspeed data to maintain safe flight envelopes.",
      "source": "target",
